      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Emgage Foundation demonstrates a lean operational model that prioritizes direct program delivery. Their <cite id=\"5\">93.3% program expense ratio</cite> suggests that administrative and fundraising costs are kept to an absolute minimum or covered by specific restricted sources. This efficiency is paired with a <cite id=\"9\">Platinum Seal of Transparency from Candid</cite>, indicating a high level of voluntary data sharing. The organization also functions as a significant grantmaker, distributing <cite id=\"10\">$920,000 in domestic grants</cite> to 33 recipients, including groups like OCA-Greater Houston and the National Korean American Service & Education Consortium. This strategy allows them to <cite id=\"11\">leverage local implementing partners</cite> to scale their voter outreach across key states like Florida, Michigan, and Virginia."
      ],
      "summary": "The Emgage Foundation is a national non-partisan organization that <cite id=\"1\">informs and mobilizes Muslim American voters</cite> to support policies that empower their communities. founded in 2017, the organization focuses on <cite id=\"2\">increasing political participation and systemic representation</cite> through a variety of civic engagement programs. Their flagship initiative, the <cite id=\"3\">Million Muslim Votes campaign</cite>, works alongside programs like the Emerging Leaders Program and the Muslim Civic Table to build long-term political infrastructure. Financially, the organization reported <cite id=\"4\">total revenue of $4,918,661</cite> in 2023. A notable feature of their financial model is their <cite id=\"5\">93.3% program expense ratio</cite>, which indicates that all reported expenses are directed toward their civic mission. Furthermore, the foundation demonstrates <cite id=\"6\">exceptional fundraising efficiency</cite>, spending only $0.01 to raise every $1 in contributions. While the organization saw significant growth since its inception, it experienced a <cite id=\"7\">revenue decline of 17%</cite> in the most recent fiscal year. Despite this, the foundation maintains <cite id=\"8\">15.3 months of working capital</cite>, providing a significant buffer to sustain its advocacy and voter mobilization efforts during non-election cycles.",
